Rating: 3
A great quick and easy dish. I substituted shallots for the pearl onions(any onion would be fine), added a couple of cloves of minced garlic, used a can of diced tomatoes, drained of juice and cut back to 1/2 cup of wine (didn't want soup). I also used tilapia but I'm sure it would be great with trout as well.

Rating: 4
This was delicious! I doubled the sauce since I had a little more fish and cooked it on the charcoal grill in the oiled pan. I served it with grits. It was a restaurant quality dish and looks fabulous.

Rating: 3
I have made this several times, with trout and tilapia. Both were delicious - the tilapia being a less expensive option, at least around here. I've used shallots instead of pearl onions, and that worked fine too. Not only is this dish easy and delicious, but it's beautiful too! It really makes me feel like I'm in southern France.

Rating: 3
Great recipe. Easy to make. Have made it twice. Second time I made some modifications that I think made it better. I backed off the wine a bit (1/2 to 3/4 cup instead of 1). I substituted dill for the parsley. I substituted tomatoe sauce for the tomatoes because I was in a hurry. Finally I used snapper instead of trout. Both were really good but I think it works better with a little less wine and a whiter fish. Enjoy!

Rating: 3
Very easy to make. I used two chopped fresh vine tomatoes and one chopped yellow onion, instead of the plum tomatoes and pearl onions. It was beautiful and tasted and smelled delicious. I also used two whole (butterflied) white trout which tasted great. The only drawback was the occaisional fishbone, which were hard to pick out with the colorful and chunky sauce. I think I will try a fillet next time, as the recipe suggested.

Rating: 3
The sauce was very good. We didn't have green olives, so we used kalamata -- big mistake -- overwhelmed the dish. Also, choose your fish carefully. We used steelhead trout which was just a little too gamey. I would do it again with a white fish such as snapper, halibut, etc.

